# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ad-hoc-polymorphism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] When applied to object-oriented or procedural concepts, it is also known as function overloading or operator overloading.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] The term ad hoc in this context is not intended to be pejorative; it refers simply to the fact that this type of polymorphism is not a fundamental feature of the type system.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This is in contrast to parametric polymorphism, in which polymorphic functions are written without mention of any specific type, and can thus apply a single abstract implementation to any number of types in a transparent way.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This classification was introduced by Christopher Strachey in 1967.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Ad hoc polymorphism is a dispatch mechanism: control moving through one named function is dispatched to various other functions without having to specify the exact function being called.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Overloading allows multiple functions taking different types to be defined with the same name; the compiler or interpreter automatically ensures that the right function is called.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This way, functions appending lists of integers, lists of strings, lists of real numbers, and so on could be written, and all be called *append*—and the right *append* function would be called based on the type of lists being appended.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This differs from parametric polymorphism, in which the function would need to be written *generically*, to work with any kind of list.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Using overloading, it is possible to have a function perform two completely different things based on the type of input passed to it; this is not possible with parametric polymorphism (but would have to be achieved with switching on the type inside the generic function).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Another way to look at overloading is that a routine is uniquely identified not by its name, but by the combination of its name and the number, order and types of its parameters.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This type of polymorphism is common in object-oriented programming languages, many of which allow operators to be overloaded in a manner similar to functions (see operator overloading).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Some languages that are not dynamically typed and lack ad hoc polymorphism (including type classes) have longer function names such as `print_int`, `print_string`, etc.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This can be seen as advantage (more descriptive) or a disadvantage (overly verbose) depending on one's point of view.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] An advantage that is sometimes gained from overloading is the appearance of specialization, e.g., a function with the same name can be implemented in multiple different ways, each optimized for the particular data types that it operates on.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This can provide a convenient interface for code that needs to be specialized to multiple situations for performance reasons.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] The downside is that the type system cannot guarantee the consistency of the different implementations.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Since overloading is done at compile time, it is not a substitute for late binding as found in subtyping polymorphism.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] The previous section notwithstanding, there are other ways in which *ad hoc* polymorphism can work out.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Consider for example the Smalltalk language.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] In Smalltalk, the overloading is done at run time, as the methods ("function implementation") for each overloaded message ("overloaded function") are resolved when they are about to be executed.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This happens at run time, after the program is compiled.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Therefore, polymorphism is given by subtyping polymorphism as in other languages, and it is also extended in functionality by *ad hoc* polymorphism at run time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] A closer look will also reveal that Smalltalk provides a slightly different variety of *ad hoc* polymorphism.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Since Smalltalk has a late bound execution model, and since it provides objects the ability to handle messages that are not understood, it is possible to implement functionality using polymorphism without explicitly overloading a particular message.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This may not be generally recommended practice for everyday programming, but it can be quite useful when implementing proxies.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Also, while in general terms common class method and constructor overloading is not considered polymorphism, there are more uniform languages in which classes are regular objects.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] In Smalltalk, for instance, classes are regular objects.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] In turn, this means messages sent to classes can be overloaded, and it is also possible to create objects that behave like classes without their classes inheriting from the hierarchy of classes.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] These are effective techniques that can be used to take advantage of Smalltalk's powerful reflection capabilities.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Similar arrangements are also possible in languages such as Self and Newspeak.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Thus, the name `+` actually refers to three or four completely different functions.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] This is an example of *overloading* or more specifically, *operator overloading*.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Note the ambiguity in the string types used in the last case.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Consider `"123" + "456"` in which the programmer might *naturally* assume addition rather than concatenation.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/ad-hoc-polymorphism] Overloading can therefore provide different meaning, or semantics, for an operation, as well as differing implementations.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In software engineering, **double dispatch** is a special form of multiple dispatch, and a mechanism that dispatches a function call to different concrete functions depending on the runtime types of two objects involved in the call.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In most object-oriented systems, the concrete function that is called from a function call in the code depends on the dynamic type of a single object and therefore they are known as single dispatch calls, or simply virtual function calls.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Dan Ingalls first described how to use double dispatching in Smalltalk, calling it multiple polymorphism.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The general problem addressed is how to dispatch a message to different methods depending not only on the receiver but also on the arguments.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] To that end, systems like CLOS implement multiple dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Double dispatch is another solution that gradually reduces the polymorphism on systems that do not support multiple dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Double dispatch is useful in situations where the choice of computation depends on the runtime types of its arguments.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The common idiom, as in the examples presented above, is that the selection of the appropriate algorithm is based on the call's argument types at runtime.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The call is therefore subject to all the usual additional performance costs that are associated with dynamic resolution of calls, usually more than in a language supporting only single method dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In C++, for example, a dynamic function call is usually resolved by a *single* offset calculation - which is possible because the compiler knows the location of the function in the object's method table and so can statically calculate the offset.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] A common use case is displaying an object on a display port which can be a screen or a printer, or something else entirely that doesn't exist yet.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] This is a naive implementation of how to deal with those different media.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The same would need to be written for Oval, Triangle and any other object that wants to display itself on a medium, and all would need to be rewritten if a new type of port were to be created.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The problem is that more than one degree of polymorphism exist: one for dispatching the display_on method to an object and another for selecting the right code (or method) for displaying.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] At first glance, double dispatch appears to be a natural result of function overloading.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Function overloading allows the function called to depend on the type of the argument.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Function overloading, however, is done at compile time using "name mangling" where the internal name of the function encodes the argument's type.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] For example, a function `foo(int)` may internally be called *__foo_i* and the function `foo(double)` may be called *__foo_d*.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Thus, there is no name collision, and no virtual table lookup.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] By contrast, dynamic dispatch is based on the type of the calling object, meaning it uses virtual functions (overriding) instead of function overloading, and does result in a vtable lookup.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] will print, respectively, `Asteroid hit a Spaceship` and `Asteroid hit an ApolloSpacecraft`, without using any dynamic dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] will print `ExplodingAsteroid hit a Spaceship` and `ExplodingAsteroid hit an ApolloSpacecraft` respectively, again without dynamic dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] prints `ExplodingAsteroid hit a Spaceship` and `ExplodingAsteroid hit an ApolloSpacecraft`, again as expected.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The desired behaviour is to bind these calls to the function that takes `apolloSpacecraft` as its argument, as that is the instantiated type of the variable, meaning the expected output would be `Asteroid hit an ApolloSpacecraft` and `ExplodingAsteroid hit an ApolloSpacecraft`.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] However, the output is actually `Asteroid hit a Spaceship` and `ExplodingAsteroid hit a Spaceship`.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The problem is that, while virtual functions are dispatched dynamically in C++, function overloading is done statically.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The problem described above can be resolved by simulating double dispatch, for example by using a visitor pattern.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] It prints out `Asteroid hit an ApolloSpacecraft` and `ExplodingAsteroid hit an ApolloSpacecraft`, as expected.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Within `ApolloSpacecraft::collideWith(Asteroid&)`, `asteroid` is a reference, so `asteroid.collideWith(*this)` will result in *another vtable lookup*.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In this case, `asteroid` is a reference to an `ExplodingAsteroid` so `ExplodingAsteroid::collideWith(ApolloSpacecraft&)` will be called.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In C#, when calling an instance method accepting an argument, multiple dispatch can be achieved without employing the visitor pattern.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] This is done by using traditional polymorphism while also casting the argument to *dynamic*.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The run-time binder will choose the appropriate method overload at run-time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] This decision will take into consideration the run-time type of the object instance (polymorphism) as well as the run-time type of the argument.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The Eiffel programming language can bring the concept of agents to bear on the double-dispatch problem.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The example below applies the agent language construct to the double-dispatch problem.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Consider a problem domain with various forms of SHAPE and of drawing SURFACE upon which to draw a SHAPE.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Both SHAPE and SURFACE know about a function called `draw' in themselves, but not in each other.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] We want objects of the two types to co-variantly interact with each other in a double-dispatch using a visitor pattern.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The challenge is to get a polymorphic SURFACE to draw a polymorphic SHAPE on itself.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The output example below shows the results of two SURFACE visitor objects being polymorphically passed over a list of polymorphic SHAPE objects.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The visitor code pattern is only aware of SHAPE and SURFACE generically and not of the specific type of either.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Instead, the code relies on run-time polymorphism and the mechanics of agents to achieve a highly flexible co-variant relationship between these two deferred classes and their descendants.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Before looking at SHAPE or SURFACE, we need to examine the high level decoupled use of our double-dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The visitor pattern works by way of a visitor object visiting the elements of a data structure (e.g. list, tree and so on) polymorphically, applying some action (call or agent) against the polymorphic element objects in the visited target structure.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In our example below, we make a list of polymorphic SHAPE objects, visiting each of them with a polymorphic SURFACE, asking the SHAPE to be drawn on the SURFACE.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] We start by creating a collection of SHAPE and SURFACE objects.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] We then iterate over one of the lists (SHAPE), allowing elements of the other (SURFACE) to visit each of them in turn.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In the example code above, SURFACE objects are visiting SHAPE objects.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The code makes a polymorphic call on {SURFACE}.draw indirectly by way of the `drawing_agent', which is the first call (dispatch) of the double-dispatch pattern.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Because both SURFACE and SHAPE define their own agents, our visitor code is freed from having to know what is the appropriate call to make, polymorphically or otherwise.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] This level of indirection and decoupling is simply not achievable in other common languages like C, C++ and Java except through either some form of reflection or feature overloading with signature matching.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Within the polymorphic call to {SURFACE}.draw is the call to an agent, which becomes the second polymorphic call or dispatch in the double-dispatch pattern.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The agent argument in line #19 and call in line #24 are both polymorphic and decoupled.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The agent is decoupled because the {SURFACE}.draw feature has no idea what class `a_data_agent' is based on.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] There is no way to tell what class the operation agent was derived from, so it does not have to come from SHAPE or one of its descendants.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] This is a distinct advantage of Eiffel agents over the single inheritance, dynamic and polymorphic binding of other languages.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The agent is dynamically polymorphic at run-time because the object is created in the moment it is needed, dynamically, where the version of the objectified routine is determined at that time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The only strongly bound knowledge is of the Result type of the agent signature—that is—a named TUPLE with two elements.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] However, this specific requirement is based on a demand of the enclosing feature (e.g. line #25 uses the named elements of the TUPLE to fulfill `draw' feature of SURFACE), which is necessary and has not been avoided (and perhaps cannot be).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Finally, note how only the `drawing_agent' feature is exported to ANY client!
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] This means that the visitor pattern code (who is the ONLY client of this class) only needs to know about the agent to get its job done (e.g. using the agent as the feature applied to the visited objects).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The SHAPE class has the basis (e.g. drawing data) for what is drawn, perhaps on a SURFACE, but it does not have to be.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Again, the agents provide the indirection and class agnostics required to make the co-variant relationship with SHAPE as decoupled as possible.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Additionally, please take note of the fact that SHAPE only provides `drawing_data_agent' as a fully exported feature to any client.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Therefore, the only way to interact with SHAPE, other than creation, is through the facilities of the `drawing_data_agent', which is used by ANY client to indirectly and polymorphically gather drawing data for the SHAPE!
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] A variation of the classic Spaceship example has one or more spaceship objects roaming about a universe filled with other items like rogue asteroids and space stations.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] What we want is a double-dispatch method for handling encounters (e.g. possible collisions) between two co-variant objects in our make-believe universe.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The visitor for the classic Spaceship example also has a double-dispatch mechanism.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The double-dispatch can be seen in line #35, where two indirect agents are working together to provide two co-variant calls working in perfect polymorphic concert with each other.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The `a_object' of the `visit' feature has an `encounter_agent' which is called with the sensor data of the `sensor_data_agent' coming from the `al_universe_object'.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The only exported features of a SPACE_OBJECT are the agents for encounter and sensor data, as well as the capacity to set a new position.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] As one object (the spaceship) visits each object in the universe, the sensor data is collected and passed to the visiting object in its encounter agent.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] There, the sensor data from the sensor_data_agent (that is—the data element items of the sensor_data TUPLE as returned by the sensor_data_agent query) are evaluated against the current object and a course of action is taken based on that evaluation (see `encounter' in SPACE_OBJECT below).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] This is similar to C, C++ and Java scopes of Private.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] As non-exported features, the data and routines are used only internally by each SPACE_OBJECT.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Finally, note that encounter calls to `print' do not include specific information about possible descendant classes of SPACE_OBJECT!
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The only thing found at this level in the inheritance are general relational aspects based completely on what can be known from the attributes and routines of a general SPACE_OBJECT.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The fact that the output of the `print' makes sense to us, as human beings, based on what we know or imagine about Star ships, space stations and asteroids is merely logical planning or coincidence.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The SPACE_OBJECT is not programmed with any specific knowledge of its descendants.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In our example, the ASTEROID class is used for the `Rogue' items, SPACESHIP for the two star ships and SPACESTATION for Deep Space Nine.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] In each class, the only specialization is the setting of the `type' feature and of certain properties of the object.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The `name' is supplied in the creation routine as well as the `position'.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] For example: Below is the SPACESHIP example.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] So, any SPACESHIP in our universe is dock-able, manned and maneuverable.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Other objects, like Asteroids are none of these things.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] A SPACESTATION, on the other hand, is both dock-able and manned, but is not maneuverable.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Thus, when one object has an encounter with another, it first checks to see if the positions put them in the vicinity of each other and if they are, then the objects interact based upon their basic properties.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Note that objects with the same type and name are considered to the same object, so an interaction is logically disallowed.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] With regards to double-dispatch, Eiffel allows the designer and programmer to further remove a level of direct object-to-object knowledge by decoupling class routines from their classes by way of making them agents and then passing those agents instead of making direct object feature calls.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The agents also have specific signatures and possible results (in the case of queries), making them ideal static type checking vehicles without giving up specific object details.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The agents are fully polymorphic so that the resulting code has only the specific knowledge required to get its local job done.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] Otherwise, there is no maintenance burden added by having specific internal class feature knowledge spread around many co-variant objects.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] The use and mechanics of agents ensure this.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] One possible downside of the use of agents is that an agent is computationally more expensive than its direct call counterpart.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] With this in mind, one ought never to presume the use of agents in the double-dispatch and their application in visitor patterns.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] If one can clearly see a design limit as to the domain of class types that will be involved in the co-variant interactions, then a direct call is the more efficient solution in terms of computational expense.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/double-dispatch] However, if the class domain of participating types is expected to grow or differ substantially, then agents present an excellent solution to lessening the maintenance burden in the double-dispatch pattern.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] In computer science, **dynamic dispatch** is the process of selecting which implementation of a polymorphic operation (method or function) to call at run time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] It is commonly employed in, and considered a prime characteristic of, object-oriented programming (OOP) languages and systems.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Object-oriented systems model a problem as a set of interacting objects that enact operations referred to by name.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Polymorphism is the phenomenon wherein somewhat interchangeable objects each expose an operation of the same name but possibly differing in behavior.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] As an example, a File object and a Database object both have a StoreRecord method that can be used to write a personnel record to storage.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] A program holds a reference to an object which may be either a File object or a Database object.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Which one it is may have been determined by a run-time setting, and at this stage, the program may not know or care which.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] When the program calls StoreRecord on the object, something needs to choose which behavior gets enacted.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] If one thinks of OOP as sending messages to objects, then in this example the program sends a StoreRecord message to an object of unknown type, leaving it to the run-time support system to dispatch the message to the right object.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The object enacts whichever behavior it implements.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Dynamic dispatch contrasts with *static dispatch*, in which the implementation of a polymorphic operation is selected at compile time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The purpose of dynamic dispatch is to defer the selection of an appropriate implementation until the run time type of a parameter (or multiple parameters) is known.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Dynamic dispatch is different from late binding (also known as dynamic binding).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Name binding associates a name with an operation.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] A polymorphic operation has several implementations, all associated with the same name.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Bindings can be made at compile time or (with late binding) at run time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] With dynamic dispatch, one particular implementation of an operation is chosen at run time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] While dynamic dispatch does not imply late binding, late binding does imply dynamic dispatch, since the implementation of a late-bound operation is not known until run time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The choice of which version of a method to call may be based either on a single object, or on a combination of objects.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The former is called *single dispatch* and is directly supported by common object-oriented languages such as Smalltalk, C++, Java, C#, Objective-C, Swift, JavaScript, and Python.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] This is thought of as sending a message named divide with parameter divisor to dividend.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] An implementation will be chosen based only on dividend's type (perhaps rational, floating point, matrix), disregarding the type or value of divisor.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] By contrast, some languages dispatch methods or functions based on the combination of operands; in the division case, the types of the dividend and divisor together determine which divide operation will be performed.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Examples of languages that support multiple dispatch are Common Lisp, Dylan, and Julia.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] A language may be implemented with different dynamic dispatch mechanisms.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The choices of the dynamic dispatch mechanism offered by a language to a large extent alter the programming paradigms that are available or are most natural to use within a given language.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Normally, in a typed language, the dispatch mechanism will be performed based on the type of the arguments (most commonly based on the type of the receiver of a message).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Languages with weak or no typing systems often carry a dispatch table as part of the object data for each object.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] This allows **instance behaviour** as each instance may map a given message to a separate method.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Dynamic dispatch will always incur an overhead so some languages offer static dispatch for particular methods.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] C++ uses early binding and offers both dynamic and static dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] To get dynamic dispatch the programmer must declare a method as virtual.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] C++ compilers typically implement dynamic dispatch with a data structure called a virtual function table (vtable) that defines the name-to-implementation mapping for a given class as a set of member function pointers.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] This is purely an implementation detail, as the C++ specification does not mention vtables.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Instances of that type will then store a pointer to this table as part of their instance data, complicating scenarios when multiple inheritance is used.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Since C++ does not support late binding, the virtual table in a C++ object cannot be modified at runtime, which limits the potential set of dispatch targets to a finite set chosen at compile time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Type overloading does not produce dynamic dispatch in C++ as the language considers the types of the message parameters part of the formal message name.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] This means that the message name the programmer sees is not the formal name used for binding.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] In Go, Rust and Nim, a more versatile variation of early binding is used.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Vtable pointers are carried with object references as 'fat pointers' ('interfaces' in Go, or 'trait objects' in Rust).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] This decouples the supported interfaces from the underlying data structures.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Each compiled library needn't know the full range of interfaces supported in order to correctly use a type, just the specific vtable layout that they require.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Code can pass around different interfaces to the same piece of data to different functions.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] This versatility comes at the expense of extra data with each object reference, which is problematic if many such references are stored persistently.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The term *fat pointer* simply refers to a pointer with additional associated information.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The additional information may be a vtable pointer for dynamic dispatch described above, but is more commonly the associated object's size to describe e.g. a *slice*.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Smalltalk uses a type-based message dispatcher.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Each instance has a single type whose definition contains the methods.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] When an instance receives a message, the dispatcher looks up the corresponding method in the message-to-method map for the type and then invokes the method.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Because a type can have a chain of base types, this look-up can be expensive.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] A naive implementation of Smalltalk's mechanism would seem to have a significantly higher overhead than that of C++ and this overhead would be incurred for every message that an object receives.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Real Smalltalk implementations often use a technique known as inline caching that makes method dispatch very fast.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Inline caching basically stores the previous destination method address and object class of the call site (or multiple pairs for multi-way caching).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The cached method is initialized with the most common target method (or just the cache miss handler), based on the method selector.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] When the method call site is reached during execution, it just calls the address in the cache.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] A fast implementation may have multiple cache entries and it often only takes a couple of instructions to get execution to the correct method on an initial cache miss.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] The common case will be a cached class match, and execution will just continue in the method.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Out-of-line caching can also be used in the method invocation logic, using the object class and method selector.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] In one design, the class and method selector are hashed, and used as an index into a method dispatch cache table.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] As Smalltalk is a reflective language, many implementations allow mutating individual objects into objects with dynamically generated method lookup tables.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] This allows altering object behavior on a per object basis.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] A whole category of languages known as prototype-based languages has grown from this, the most famous of which are Self and JavaScript.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Careful design of the method dispatch caching allows even prototype-based languages to have high-performance method dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Many other dynamically typed languages, including Python, Ruby, Objective-C and Groovy use similar approaches.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/dynamic-dispatch] Dynamic dispatch is not built in to C like other languages, but it is still possible by manually managing function pointers.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] In some programming languages, **function overloading** or **method overloading** is the ability to create multiple functions of the same name with different implementations.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Calls to an overloaded function will run a specific implementation of that function appropriate to the context of the call, allowing one function call to perform different tasks depending on context.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] For example, doTask() and doTask(object o) are overloaded functions.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] To call the latter, an object must be passed as a parameter, whereas the former does not require a parameter, and is called with an empty parameter field.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] A common error would be to assign a default value to the object in the second function, which would result in an *ambiguous call* error, as the compiler wouldn't know which of the two methods to use.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Another example is a Print(object o) function that executes different actions based on whether it's printing text or photos.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] The two different functions may be overloaded as Print(text_object T); Print(image_object P).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] If we write the overloaded print functions for all objects our program will "print", we never have to worry about the type of the object, and the correct function call again, the call is always: Print(something).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Languages not supporting function overloading include C, Python, Rust, and Zig.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Function overloading is usually associated with statically-typed programming languages that enforce type checking in function calls.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] An overloaded function is a set of different functions that are callable with the same name.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] For any particular call, the compiler determines which overloaded function to use and resolves this at compile time.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] This is true for programming languages such as Java.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Function overloading differs from forms of polymorphism where the choice is made at runtime, e.g. through virtual functions, instead of statically.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] In the above example, the volume of each component is calculated using one of the three functions named "volume", with selection based on the differing number and type of actual parameters.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Constructors, used to create instances of an object, may also be overloaded in some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Because in many languages the constructor's name is predetermined by the name of the class, it would seem that there can be only one constructor.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Whenever multiple constructors are needed, they are to be implemented as overloaded functions.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] In C++, default constructors take no parameters, instantiating the object members with their appropriate default values, "which is normally zero for numeral fields and empty string for string fields".
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] The drawback to this is that it takes two steps to change the value of the created Bill object.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] By overloading the constructor, one could pass the tip and total as parameters at creation.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] This shows the overloaded constructor with two parameters.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] This overloaded constructor is placed in the class as well as the original constructor we used before.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Now a function that creates a new Bill object could pass two values into the constructor and set the data members in one step.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] This can be useful in increasing program efficiency and reducing code length.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Another reason for constructor overloading can be to enforce mandatory data members.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] In this case the default constructor is declared private or protected (or preferably deleted since C++11) to make it inaccessible from outside.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] For the Bill above total might be the only constructor parameter – since a Bill has no sensible default for total – whereas tip defaults to 0.15.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Two issues interact with and complicate function overloading: Name masking (due to scope) and implicit type conversion.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] The first is taken in C++: "in C++, there is no overloading across scopes." As a result, to obtain an overload set with functions declared in different scopes, one needs to explicitly import the functions from the outer scope into the inner scope, with the `using` keyword.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Implicit type conversion complicates function overloading because if the types of parameters do not exactly match the signature of one of the overloaded functions, but can match after type conversion, resolution depends on which type conversion is chosen.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] These can combine in confusing ways: An inexact match declared in an inner scope can mask an exact match declared in an outer scope, for instance.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] If a method is designed with an excessive number of overloads, it may be difficult for developers to discern which overload is being called simply by reading the code.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] This is particularly true if some of the overloaded parameters are of types that are inherited types of other possible parameters (for example "object").
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] An IDE can perform the overload resolution and display (or navigate to) the correct overload.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/function-overloading] Type-based overloading can also hamper code maintenance, where code updates can accidentally change which method overload is chosen by the compiler.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Developers of computer software typically organize source code into named blocks variously called subroutines, procedures, subprograms, functions, or methods.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The code in the function is executed by *calling* it – executing a piece of code that references its *name*.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] This transfers control temporarily to the called function; when the function's execution has completed, control is typically transferred back to the instruction in the *caller* that follows the reference.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Function names are usually selected so as to be descriptive of the function's purpose.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] It is sometimes desirable to give several functions the same name, often because they perform conceptually similar tasks, but operate on different types of input data.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] In such cases, the name reference at the function call site is not sufficient for identifying the block of code to be executed.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Instead, the number and type of the arguments to the function call are also used to select among several function implementations.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] In contrast, in languages with multiple dispatch, the selected method is simply the one whose arguments match the number and type of the function call.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] There is no *special* argument that *owns* the function/method carried out in a particular call.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Many languages such as C++ offer robust function overloading but do not offer dynamic multiple dispatch (C++ only permits dynamic single dispatch through use of virtual functions).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] When working with languages that can discriminate data types at compile time, selecting among the alternatives can occur then.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The act of creating such alternative functions for compile time selection is usually referred to as overloading a function.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] In programming languages that defer data type identification until run time (i.e., late binding), selection among alternative functions must occur then, based on the dynamically determined types of function arguments.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Functions whose alternative implementations are selected in this manner are referred to most generally as *multimethods*.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] There is some run-time cost associated with dynamically dispatching function calls.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] In some languages, the distinction between overloading and multimethods can be blurred, with the compiler determining whether compile time selection can be applied to a given function call, or whether slower run time dispatch is needed.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] There are several known issues with dynamic-dispatch, both single and multiple.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] While many of these issues are solved for single-dispatch, which has been a standard feature in object-oriented programming languages for decades, these issues become more complicated in the multiple-dispatch case.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] In most popular programming languages, source code is delivered and deployed in granules of functionality which we will here call *packages*; actual terminology for this concept varies between language.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Each package may contain multiple type, value, and function definitions, packages are often compiled separately in languages with a compilation step, and a non-cyclical dependency relationship may exist.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] A complete program is a set of packages, with a *main package* which may depend on several other packages, and the whole program consisting of the transitive closure of the dependency relationship.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The so-called expression problem relates to the ability for code in a depending package to extend behaviors (functions or datatypes) defined in a base package from within an including package, without modifying the source to the base package.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Traditional single-dispatch OO languages make it trivial to add new datatypes but not new functions; traditional functional languages tend to have the opposite effect, and multiple dispatch, if implemented correctly, allows both.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] It is generally desirable that for any given invocation of a multi-method, there be at most one "best" candidate among implementation cases of the multi-method, and/or that if there is not, that this be resolved in a predictable and deterministic fashion, including failure.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Non-deterministic behavior is undesirable.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Efficient implementation of single-dispatch, including in programming languages that are separately compiled to object code and linked with a low-level (not-language-aware) linker, including dynamically at program load/start time or even under the direction of the application code, are well known.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] However, the vtable method uses the function name and not the argument type as its lookup key, and does not scale to the multiple dispatch case.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] (It also depends on the object-oriented paradigm of methods being features of classes, not standalone entities independent of any particular datatype).
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Efficient implementation of multiple-dispatch remains an ongoing research problem.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] To estimate how often multiple dispatch is used in practice, Muschevici et al. studied programs that use dynamic dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] They analyzed nine applications, mostly compilers, written in six different languages: Common Lisp Object System, Dylan, Cecil, MultiJava, Diesel, and Nice.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Their results show that 13–32% of generic functions use the dynamic type of one argument, while 2.7–6.5% of them use the dynamic type of multiple arguments.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The remaining 65–93% of generic functions have one concrete method (overrider), and thus are not considered to use the dynamic types of their arguments.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Further, the study reports that 2–20% of generic functions had two and 3–6% had three concrete function implementations.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The numbers decrease rapidly for functions with more concrete overriders.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The theory of multiple dispatching languages was first developed by Castagna et al., by defining a model for overloaded functions with late binding.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] It yielded the first formalization of the problem of type variance (covariance and contravariance) of object-oriented languages and a solution to the problem of binary methods.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Distinguishing multiple and single dispatch may be made clearer by an example.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Imagine a game that has, among its (user-visible) objects, spaceships and asteroids.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] When two objects collide, the program may need to do different things according to what has just hit what.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] C# introduced support for dynamic multimethods in version 4 (April 2010) using the 'dynamic' keyword.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The following example demonstrates multimethods.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Like many other statically-typed languages, C# also supports static method overloading.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Microsoft expects that developers will choose static typing over dynamic typing in most scenarios.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The 'dynamic' keyword supports interoperability with COM objects and dynamically-typed .NET languages.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The example below uses features introduced in C# 9 and C# 10.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Groovy is a general purpose Java compatible/interusable JVM language, which, contrary to Java, uses late binding / multiple dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Explicit testing and "dynamic casting" are not used.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] In the presence of multiple dispatch, the traditional idea of methods as being defined in classes and contained in objects becomes less appealing—each *collide-with* method above is attached to two different classes, not one.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Hence, the special syntax for method invocation generally disappears, so that method invocation looks exactly like ordinary function invocation, and methods are grouped not in classes but in generic functions.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Julia has built-in multiple dispatch, and it is central to the language design.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Raku, like Perl, uses proven ideas from other languages, and type systems have shown themselves to offer compelling advantages in compiler-side code analysis and powerful user-side semantics via multiple dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] It has both multimethods, and multisubs.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Since most operators are subroutines, it also has multiple dispatched operators.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Along with the usual type constraints, it also has *where* constraints that allow making very specialized subroutines.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] In languages that do not support multiple dispatch at the language definition or syntactic level, it is often possible to add multiple dispatch using a library extension.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] JavaScript and TypeScript do not support multimethods at the syntax level, but it is possible to add multiple dispatch via a library.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] For example, the *multimethod package* provides an implementation of multiple dispatch, generic functions.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Multiple dispatch can be added to Python using a library extension.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] For example, using the module *multimethod.py* and also with the module *multimethods.py* which provides CLOS-style multimethods for Python without changing the underlying syntax or keywords of the language.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Functionally, this is very similar to the CLOS example, but the syntax is conventional Python.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] and then it goes on to define the multimethod decorator.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The PEAK-Rules package provides multiple dispatch with a syntax similar to the above example.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The Reg library also supports multiple and predicate dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] With the introduction of type hints, multiple dispatch is possible with even simpler syntax.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] C does not have dynamic dispatch, so it must be implemented manually in some form.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Often an enum is used to identify the subtype of an object.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Dynamic dispatch can be done by looking up this value in a function pointer branch table.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] With the C Object System library, C does support dynamic dispatch similar to CLOS.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] It is fully extensible and does not need any manual handling of the methods.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Dynamic message (methods) are dispatched by the dispatcher of COS, which is faster than Objective-C.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] As of 2021, C++ natively supports only single dispatch, though adding multi-methods (multiple dispatch) was proposed by Bjarne Stroustrup (and collaborators) in 2007.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The *YOMM2* library provides a fast, orthogonal implementation of open multimethods.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The syntax for declaring open methods is inspired by a proposal for a native C++ implementation.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The library requires that the user registers all the classes used as virtual arguments (and their sub-classes), but does not require any modifications to existing code.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Methods are implemented as ordinary inline C++ functions; they can be overloaded and they can be passed by pointer.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] There is no limit on the number of virtual arguments, and they can be arbitrarily mixed with non-virtual arguments.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The library uses a combination of techniques (compressed dispatch tables, collision free integer hash table) to implement method calls in constant time, while mitigating memory usage.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Dispatching a call to an open method with a single virtual argument takes only 15–30% more time than calling an ordinary virtual member function, when a modern optimizing compiler is used.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Stroustrup mentions in *The Design and Evolution of C++* that he liked the concept of multimethods and considered implementing it in C++ but claims to have been unable to find an efficient sample implementation (comparable to virtual functions) and resolve some possible type ambiguity problems.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] He then states that although the feature would still be nice to have, that it can be approximately implemented using double dispatch or a type based lookup table as outlined in the C/C++ example above so is a low priority feature for future language revisions.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] As of 2021, as do many other object-oriented programming languages, D natively supports only single dispatch.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] However, it is possible to emulate open multimethods as a library function in D.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] The *openmethods* library is an example.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/multiple-dispatch] Run time `instanceof` checks at one or both levels can also be used.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] In computer programming, **operator overloading**, sometimes termed *operator ad hoc polymorphism*, is a specific case of polymorphism, where different operators have different implementations depending on their arguments.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Operator overloading is generally defined by a programming language, a programmer, or both.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Operator overloading is syntactic sugar, and is used because it allows programming using notation nearer to the target domain and allows user-defined types a similar level of syntactic support as types built into a language.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] It is common, for example, in scientific computing, where it allows computing representations of mathematical objects to be manipulated with the same syntax as on paper.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Operator overloading does not change the expressive power of a language (with functions), as it can be emulated using function calls.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] However, the former syntax reflects common mathematical usage.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Addition is a binary operation, which means it has two operands.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] In C++, the arguments being passed are the operands, and the `temp` object is the returned value.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Like with the previous examples, in the last example operator overloading is done within the class.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] In C++, after overloading the less-than operator (`operator<`), standard sorting functions can be used to sort some classes.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Starting in C++20 with the introduction of the three-way comparison operator (`operator<=>`), all the order operators can be defined by just defining that operator.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] The three-way comparison operator exists in many languages, including C++, Python, Rust, Swift, and PHP.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Other languages, such as Java and C# instead use a method `Comparable.compareTo()`.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Operator overloading has been criticized because it allows programmers to reassign the semantics of operators depending on the types of their operands.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] For example, the use of the `<<` operator in C++ `a << b` shifts the bits in the variable `a` left by `b` bits if `a` and `b` are of an integer type, but if `a` is an output stream then the above code will attempt to write a `b` to the stream.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Another, more subtle, issue with operators is that certain rules from mathematics can be wrongly expected or unintentionally assumed.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] For example, the commutativity of + (i.e. that `a + b == b + a`) does not always apply; an example of this occurs when the operands are strings, since + is commonly overloaded to perform a concatenation of strings (i.e.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] A typical counter to this argument comes directly from mathematics: While + is commutative on integers (and more generally any complex number), it is not commutative for other "types" of variables.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] In practice, + is not even always associative, for example with floating-point values due to rounding errors.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Another example: In mathematics, multiplication is commutative for real and complex numbers but not commutative in matrix multiplication.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] A classification of some common programming languages is made according to whether their operators are overloadable by the programmer and whether the operators are limited to a predefined set.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] The ALGOL 68 specification allowed operator overloading.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Note that no special declaration is needed to *overload* an operator, and the programmer is free to create new operators.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Ada supports overloading of operators from its inception, with the publication of the Ada 83 language standard.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] However, the language designers chose to preclude the definition of new operators.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Only extant operators in the language may be overloaded, by defining new functions with identifiers such as "+", "*", "&" etc.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Subsequent revisions of the language (in 1995 and 2005) maintain the restriction to overloading of extant operators.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] In C++, operator overloading is more refined than in ALGOL 68.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Java language designers at Sun Microsystems chose to omit overloading.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] When asked about operator overloading, Brian Goetz of Oracle responded "Value types first, then we can talk about it.", suggesting that it could potentially be added after Project Valhalla.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Python allows operator overloading through the implementation of methods with special names.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] For example, the addition (+) operator can be overloaded by implementing the method `obj.__add__(self, other)`.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Ruby allows operator overloading as syntactic sugar for simple method calls.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Lua allows operator overloading as syntactic sugar for method calls with the added feature that if the first operand doesn't define that operator, the method for the second operand will be used.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Microsoft added operator overloading to C# in 2001 and to Visual Basic .NET in 2003.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Scala treats all operators as methods and thus allows operator overloading by proxy.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] In Raku, the definition of all operators is delegated to lexical functions, and so, using function definitions, operators can be overloaded or new operators added.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Since "multi" was used, the function gets added to the list of multidispatch candidates, and "`+`" is only overloaded for the case where the type constraints in the function signature are met.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] While the capacity for overloading includes `+`, `*`, `>=`, the postfix and term `i`, and so on, it also allows for overloading various brace operators: `[x, y]`, `x[y]`, `x{y}`, and `x(y)`.
[src:ad-hoc-polymorphism/operator-overloading] Operator overloading in Rust is accomplished by implementing the traits in `std::ops`.
